ing" class="sc-avest iZvAhG pf-223_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-hGnimi cpnKBf pf-222_">4. Adding essential oils</span></h4><p class="sc-hYQoXb koTnzq pf-226_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-hGnimi cpnKBf pf-225_">If adding essential oils, add 8-15 drops during this step.</span></p><h4 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-avest iZvAhG pf-232_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-hGnimi cpnKBf pf-231_">5. Slowly add the liquid to the dry mixture</span></h4><p class="sc-hYQoXb koTnzq pf-235_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-hGnimi cpnKBf pf-234_">Slowly add the liquid to the dry mixture. really slow. Like a teaspoon at a time. You don't want your DIY bath bomb to explode prematurely. Stir as you go. If you see the mixture fizzing or foaming, you may be adding the liquid too quickly, slow down adding the wet mixture. After mixing the wet and dry ingredients, take a small amount in your hands and squeeze together. It should stick together in 1-2 pieces. If it's still too powdery to stick together, just slowly add a little water and squeeze it again. You should end up with a mixture that barely clumps, like damp sand.
